Public Protector Busisiwe Mkhwebane. AFP/Phill Magakoe JOHANNESBURG - The Constitutional Court has paved the way for Parliament to continue its impeachment process against Public Protector Busisiwe Mkhwebane. In a unanimous decision, the court sided with National Assembly Speaker, Nosiviwe Mapisa-Nqakula and the Democratic Alliance. READ: Mkhwebane wants impeachment halted after court ruling The apex court found that it is permissible to appoint a judge to the independent panel set up to investigate Mkhwebane’s fitness to hold office. After Mkhwebane’s minor victory in the High Court, the speaker and the DA applied for a direct appeal on an urgent basis. This was granted by the Constitutional Court. The court agreed with the High Court that Mkhwebane should have the right to legal representation. READ: Public Protector challenges Parliament's impeachment rules This right was limited in the newly drafted rules occasioned by the complaints of misconduct and incompetence But Mkhwebane lost her cross-appeal in its entirety.